## Example 1, Instead of partial fractions {.scrollable}
::: callout-tip

## Example

Calculate $$\mathscr{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{(s-2)(s-3)}\right\}$$ w/o using partial fractions.

::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"}
## Solution

$$\mathscr{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{(s-2)(s-3)}\right\}=\int_0^t f(z)g(t-z)\,dz$$
$$=\int_0^t e^{2z}e^{3(t-z)}dz$$

$$=e^{3t}\int_0^t e^{-z}dz$$

$$=e^{3t} \left(\frac{e^{-z}}{-1}\Big|_0^t\right)$$

$$=-e^{3t} \left(e^{-t}-e^0\right)$$
$$=e^{3t} \left(1-e^{-t}\right)$$
$$=e^{3t} -e^{2t}$$
checking with maxima-cas:

```maxima
partfrac(1/((s-2)*(s-3)),s);
ilt(%,s,t);
```
$${{e}^{3 t}}\operatorname{-}{{e}^{2 t}}$$

:::
:::

## Convolution!

![convolution is a mathematical operation on two functions ($f$ and $g$) that produces a third function $(f*g)$ that expresses how the shape of one is modified by the other](Convolution.gif){width=6in}


## Property of convolution function

$$\mathscr{L}\{(f*g)(t)\}=\mathscr{L}\{f(t)\}\mathscr{L}\{g(t)\}$$

## Example 1, solving IVP {.scrollable}
::: callout-tip

## Example

Suppose $y=f(t)$ is the solution of the constant-coefficient homogeneous initial value problem
$$y''+Py'+Qy=0,\qquad y(0)=0,\quad y'(0)=1$$
Then the solution of the inhomogeneous initial value problem

$$y''+Py'+Qy=g(t),\qquad y(0)=0,\quad y'(0)=0$$

is $$y(t)=(f*g)(t)$$


::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"}
## Solution

Taking the Laplace Transform of homogeneous eqn:

$$s^2Y-1+PsY+QY=0$$
$$Y=\frac{1}{s^2+Ps+Q}$$
$$y=f(t)=\mathscr{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{1}{s^2+Ps+Q}\right\}$$
Taking Laplace transform of non-homogeneous case

$$s^2Y+PsY+QY=G$$
$$Y=\frac{G}{s^2+Ps+Q}$$
$$y(t)=\mathscr{L}^{-1}\left\{\frac{G}{s^2+Ps+Q}\right\}$$
$$=\mathscr{L}^{-1}\left\{G(s)F(s)\right\}$$
$$=(f*g)(t)$$
$$\hspace{3in}\square$$
:::
:::


## Volterra Integral Equation
::: callout-note
## Definition

An equation of the form

$$y(t)=f(t)+ \int_0^t k(t-\tau)y(\tau)\,d\tau$$

is a Volterra integral equation. Here $f$ and $k$ are given functions and $y$ is unknown. Since the integral on the right is a convolution integral, the convolution theorem provides a convenient formula for solving it. Laplace!

$$Y = F + YK$$ 
$$Y=\frac{F}{1-K}$$
:::

## Example 2
::: {.callout-tip} 
## Example
Solve

$$y(t)=1+2\int_0^t e^{-2(t-\tau)} y(\tau)\,d\tau.$$

::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"}
## Solution

$$Y = \frac{1}{s}+2 \left(\frac{1}{s-^-2}\right)Y$$
$$Y\left(1-\frac{2}{s+2}\right)=\frac{1}{s}$$
$$Y\left(\frac{s+2}{s+2}-\frac{2}{s+2}\right)=\frac{1}{s}$$

$$Y=\frac{s+2}{s^2}$$
$$Y=\frac{1}{s}+\frac{2}{s^2}$$
$$\Rightarrow$$

$$y(t)=1+ 2t$$

:::
:::


## Example 3 {.scrollable}
::: {.callout-tip} 

## Example 

Solve `Integrodifferentiable equation`

$$y'(t)=1+\int_0^t y(z)\,dz\qquad, y(0)=0$$


:::{.fragment}

::: {.callout-caution collapse="true"}
## Solution

Applying Laplace:
$$sY=\frac{1}{s}+\mathscr{L}\left\{\int_0^t y(z)\,dz\right\}$$
$$sY=\frac{1}{s}+\mathscr{L}\left\{\int_0^t (y(z)*1)\,dz\right\}$$

$$sY=\frac{1}{s}+\mathscr{L}\left\{\int_0^t (y(z)*(t-z)^0)\,dz\right\}$$


$$sY=\frac{1}{s}+\mathscr{L}\{y(t)\}\mathscr{L}\{t^0\}$$
$$sY=\frac{1}{s}+Y\frac{1}{s}$$
$$sY-Y\frac{1}{s}=\frac{1}{s}$$
$$Y\left(\frac{s^2}{s}-\frac{1}{s}\right)=\frac{1}{s}$$
$$Y=\frac{1}{s^2-1}$$
$$\Rightarrow \boxed{y(t)=\sinh t}\,,\qquad t>1$$
:::
:::
:::

